    %section
      %h1 How risky are shares?
      %p
        Shares as an asset class are perhaps the riskiest amongst all asset classes. Further if a person was to be involved in trading as opposed to investing, the risk increases all the more. Consider this: During the 2008 subprime crisis, in spite of the Indian economy being insulated from most of the global mess, in no more than 14 months the share markets declined by more than 50% from their January 2008 highs. Later when the panic settled down, the equity markets rose by 100% from their March 2009 lows. During this time gold traded in a range between X-Y while your fixed deposits would have yielded you a standard Z% return. Also while the overall index declined by a little more than 50%, there were several shares that declined by more than 80%. Similarly in the run up too, several shares increased by 200-300% from their lows. To shield yourself from such extreme volatility, it is important you 
        #{link_to 'diversify', main_app.page_path('investment_education/investment-diversification')} your portfolio across several shares and sectors.
    %section
      %h1 How to invest in shares?
      %p
        An investor can invest directly in shares of a company or through equity
        #{link_to 'mutual funds and ETFs', main_app.page_path('investment_education/mutual-funds-etf')}.
        As mentioned above, while investing in shares directly, it is important that you concentrate on diversifying your portfolio across shares and sectors. Another mix of asset classes within shares can are: large caps, midcaps and small caps.
      %p
        Mutual funds are collective pools of investments actively managed by professionals. There are several mutual funds dedicated towards investing in equities.  ETFs are passively managed investment pools that are designed to track the performance of certain index. Investing in mutual funds and ETFs, offer the advantage of diversification at a reduced cost.
    %section
      %h1 How are shares taxed?
      %p
        From tax reasons, your holdings are divided into long term holdings and short term holdings. Any holding for a period above 1 year is considered a long term and gains on it are exempt from tax. A holding period of less than a year is considered a short term and capital gains over the short term are subject to 15% short term capital gain tax.
      %p
        Dividends received are taxed at the company’s end before they are distributed to the shareholder and as such are tax free in hand of the investor.
